## Abstract

This paper presents a comprehensive machine learning approach to predict customer subscription to bank term deposits using the Bank Marketing dataset from UCI Machine Learning Repository. We compare three different classification methods—Decision Tree, Linear Regression (as a Linear Probability Model), and Random Forest—under two distinct data preprocessing strategies. Our experimental results demonstrate that Random Forest achieves the highest accuracy of 90.99%, outperforming both Decision Tree (88.54%) and Linear Regression (90.15%). Additionally, we conduct extensive feature analysis and cross-analysis to identify key factors influencing customer decisions. Our findings reveal that call duration, customer age, occupation (especially students and retirees), and economic indicators (particularly Euribor3m) are the most significant predictors. The study also identifies optimal campaign strategies, suggesting that cellular contact, March-December period, and 1-2 contact attempts yield the highest conversion rates. These insights provide actionable recommendations for banking institutions to optimize their telemarketing campaigns.

**Keywords:** Machine Learning, Bank Marketing, Term Deposit Prediction, Random Forest, Customer Segmentation, Classification

